MERA and rejection sampling

Ernesto Carrella

10/24/2020

We’ve been struggling to get the MERA output for 712-718. We can produce some output from the questionnaire but it’s not really taking into account the fact that we have three years of low SPR. We tried multiple times to get MERA’s SRA working but we keep getting ignored or the results are absurdly positive.
So here I use rejection sampling to achieve the same. I have to go through the DLM-toolkit rather than MERA,

Rejection sampling here is pretty simple: take only the simulations whose last 3 years had SPR below 20% (same condition as POSEIDON in 718). Here I am using Peter’s formula (linear selectivity; cutting off 1% of the smallest catches; 5cm bins) and TNC numbers (\(M\),\(K\),\(L_{\infty}\),etc.). I run 5000 fisheries for the MSE, and 328 are accepted. #* 5000 runs from the questionaire, 328 are accepted.

Questionnaire only

In general the questionaire is very positive both in terms of probability of not overfishing and in terms of long term yield. If you care more about not-overfishing then you should stick with some TACs + Indicator (Itarget1 or IT10), while amazingly long term yield is better with just effort fixed at 75% (curE75).

Conditioned on SPR

When we condition however we get a much more pessimistic view of the world where indicator + TAC strategies keep their low probability of overfishing but crash their long term yield while most effort policies overfish dramatically but have higher yields. Low yields forever vs overfishing forever, pick your poison. This is more in line with what I expected looking at SPRs and to me makes a lot of sense Keep in mind that TAC policies are there for comparisons since we have neither a good indicator nor a credible way to put quotas.

Conditioned on SPR + high M/K

As always, whenever we use/condition on SPR the result is always just a rehash of the following: “What is the M/K and how off are you?”. This we know from POSEIDON but it’s easy to show here too. Take the 328 runs that were accepted (SPR low for three years) and now pick from those only the runs whose true M/K is above 1.2 (I think the M/K ratio MERA uses is straight out of FishLife so it is quite wide). That leaves you with 182 simulations.

When we add this second condition, we are magically teleported back into the world of optimism where all policies work out great! From this we learn the same lesson we learn in all of our indonesian work: “Using SPR as evidence always always always turns out to just be a question on M/K priors”
